\chapter{Overview}
\label{learnlog}

The [[learnlog]] package provides automatic logging of student code
development.
Students add \mintinline{python}{import learnlog} as the first line of
their Python files.
When the program runs, the import triggers a chain of actions: it
detects which script is running, stages any source code changes into a
hidden Git repository, wraps the standard streams to capture all I/O,
and registers cleanup handlers that finalise the log entry when the
program exits.

The design is guided by two constraints:
\begin{description}
\item[Transparency] The student's program must behave identically
  whether or not learnlog is imported.
  We must never crash, hang, or alter the program's output.
\item[Crash resilience] Even if the program is killed mid-execution, we
  want to record as much as possible.
  We achieve this by committing the run header \emph{before} the
  program executes and amending it with results afterwards.
\end{description}


\section{Code overview}

<<[[__init__.py]]>>=
"""Automatic logging of student code development.

Import this module to record every program run: source code changes,
command-line arguments, stdin/stdout/stderr, and errors.  Data is
stored in a hidden ``.learnlog/`` Git repository.
"""

import sys
import os
import datetime
import atexit
import traceback

from learnlog.capture import IOLog, StreamCapture, InputCapture
from learnlog.gitrepo import LearnlogRepo

