\section{Module state}

We need a handful of global variables to coordinate between
initialisation (at import time) and cleanup (at exit time).
The [[repo]] variable also serves as an initialisation guard: if it is
not [[None]], we have already initialised and should not do so again.
This handles the case where multiple files in the same program all
\mintinline{python}{import learnlog}.

<<module state>>=
repo = None
iolog = None
original_stdout = None
original_stderr = None
original_stdin = None
exception_info = None
start_time = None
main_script = None
main_args = None
@


\section{Initialisation}

The [[initialize]] function is called at import time.
It detects the main script, creates (or opens) the learnlog repository,
records the run header, and installs the I/O wrappers.

Why detect the main script via [[sys.argv[0]]] rather than
[[__file__]]?
Because [[__file__]] gives us the file that contains the import
statement, which might be a library module.
We want the script the student actually invoked from the command line.

The entire function is wrapped in a [[try]]/[[except]] that catches
\emph{everything}.
If learnlog fails for any reason---no Git installed, permission denied,
disk full---the student's program must still work.

<<functions>>=
def initialize():
    """Set up learnlog: detect script, init repo, wrap streams.

    Called automatically on import.  Safe to call multiple times;
    subsequent calls are no-ops.
    """
    global repo, iolog, start_time, main_script, main_args
    global original_stdout, original_stderr, original_stdin

    if repo is not None:
        return

    try:
        <<detect main script>>
        <<create repository and begin run>>
        <<install I/O wrappers>>
        <<install exception hook>>
        atexit.register(on_exit)
    except Exception:
        pass
@

<<detect main script>>=
main_script = os.path.basename(sys.argv[0])
main_args = sys.argv[1:]
start_time = datetime.datetime.now()
workdir = os.getcwd()
@

We choose the current working directory as the root rather than the
directory containing the script.
Students typically run [[python hello.py]] from the project
directory, so [[os.getcwd()]] is the natural root for the repository.

<<create repository and begin run>>=
repo = LearnlogRepo(workdir)
repo.begin_run(main_script, main_args, start_time)
@

<<install I/O wrappers>>=
iolog = IOLog()
original_stdout = sys.stdout
original_stderr = sys.stderr
original_stdin = sys.stdin
sys.stdout = StreamCapture(original_stdout, "stdout", iolog)
sys.stderr = StreamCapture(original_stderr, "stderr", iolog)
sys.stdin = InputCapture(original_stdin, iolog)
@

